The '''bar mitzvah attack''' is an attack on the [[Transport Layer Security|SSL/TLS]] protocols that exploits the use of the [[RC4]] cipher with [[weak key]]s for that cipher.<ref name="darkreading">{{cite web|url=http://www.darkreading.com/attacks-breaches/ssl-tls-suffers-bar-mitzvah-attack-/d/d-id/1319633?|title=SSL/TLS Suffers 'Bar Mitzvah Attack' |author=Kelly Jackson Higgins|date=26 March 2015|publisher=Dark Reading}}</ref><ref name=goodin20150327>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/security/2015/03/noose-around-internets-tls-system-tightens-with-2-new-decryption-attacks/|title=Noose around Internet’s TLS system tightens with 2 new decryption attacks|publisher=Ars Technica|author=Dan Goodin|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> While this affects only the first hundred or so bytes of only the very small fraction of connections that happen to use weak keys, it allows significant compromise of user security, for example by allowing the interception of password information<ref name=goodin20150327/> which could then be used for long-term exploitation.

The attack uses a vulnerability in RC4 described as the ''invariance weakness'' by Fluhrer et al. in their 2001 paper on RC4 weaknesses.<ref name=goodin20150327/><ref>Fluhrer, S., Mantin, I., and A. Shamir, "[http://www.crypto.com/papers/others/rc4_ksaproc.pdf Weaknesses in the Key Scheduling Algorithm of RC4]", Selected Areas of Cryptography: SAC 2001, [[Lecture Notes in Computer Science]] Vol. 2259, pp 1–24, 2001.</ref>

The attack is named after the [[Bar and Bat Mitzvah|bar mitzvah]] ceremony which is held at 13 years of age, because the vulnerability exploited is 13 years old<ref name="darkreading" /> and likely inspired by the naming of the unrelated [[birthday attack]].

