In [[mathematics]], a '''continuous module''' is a [[module (mathematics)|module]] ''M'' such that every submodule of ''M'' is essential in a direct summand and every submodule of ''M'' isomorphic to a direct summand is itself a direct summand. The [[endomorphism ring]] of a continuous module is a [[clean ring]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021869306004339|title=Continuous modules are clean|last=Camillo|first=V.P.|last2=Khurana|first2=D.|last3=Lam|first3=T.Y.|last4=Nicholson|first4=W.K.|last5=Zhou|first5=Y.|website=ScienceDirect|access-date=25 April 2016|doi=10.1016/j.jalgebra.2006.06.032|volume=304|pages=94–111}}</ref>

